notebook environment may not see them. The method below adds a new kernel based
on the later environment and allow to benefit from conda:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;pre class="code bash"&gt;&lt;a name="rest_code_467d4b1532e34be4b3f43a0eda560fdb-1"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;conda activate my-env
&lt;a name="rest_code_467d4b1532e34be4b3f43a0eda560fdb-2"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;conda  create -n my-env pip setuptools ipykernel &lt;span class="nv"&gt;python&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="o"&gt;=&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="m"&gt;3&lt;/span&gt;.5
&lt;a name="rest_code_467d4b1532e34be4b3f43a0eda560fdb-3"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;python -m ipykernel install --user --name my-env --display-name &lt;span class="s2"&gt;"Python (my-env)"&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</description><category>jupyter</category><category>python</category><guid>https://parisni.github.io/weblog/posts/jupyter-notebooks-and-conda/</guid><pubDate>Fri, 16 Nov 2018 18:11:17 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title>A decent python configuration</title><link>https://parisni.github.io/weblog/posts/a-decent-python-configuration/</link><dc:creator>Parisni</dc:creator><description>&lt;div class="section" id="use-anaconda"&gt;
